00:29:48,620 --> 00:29:50,872
when I'm out searching for my wife.

502
00:29:52,373 --> 00:29:55,960
It's your-- I'm sorry. I was just--
I just wanted to know...

503
00:29:57,378 --> 00:29:59,088
I'm sorry this is happening.

504
00:30:00,173 --> 00:30:01,382
I really am.

505
00:30:01,466 --> 00:30:03,510
Well, I guess I have you to thank.

506
00:30:05,386 --> 00:30:08,556
For getting Theodore to come.
He told me you talked to him.

507
00:30:08,640 --> 00:30:12,519
-He called you a kind person.
-I barely said anything. I just...

508
00:30:13,645 --> 00:30:15,146
He seems like a good kid.

509
00:30:18,024 --> 00:30:18,900
Excuse me.

510
00:30:30,620 --> 00:30:34,624
Yo, why is everyone so scared
of Sherry Conrad?

511
00:30:35,250 --> 00:30:39,838
She is fucking pathetic, right?

512
00:30:40,839 --> 00:30:43,716
I hear that her husband,

513
00:30:43,800 --> 00:30:47,804
he has to take pharmaceutical molly
just so he can get it up for her.

514
00:30:48,471 --> 00:30:49,305
Yeah.

515
00:30:50,640 --> 00:30:53,893
Oh, and please tell me
you saw that speech, right?

516
00:30:57,313 --> 00:30:59,065
I have to pee. Be right back.

517
00:31:02,193 --> 00:31:03,027
Okay.

518
00:31:05,113 --> 00:31:06,656
[dramatic music playing]

519
00:31:39,814 --> 00:31:41,941
Awful, you know?

520
00:31:42,025 --> 00:31:45,403
But if I was married
to a robot like Matthew Engler,

521
00:31:45,486 --> 00:31:47,030
probably disappear too.

522
00:31:47,113 --> 00:31:47,947
[all laughing]

523
00:31:48,031 --> 00:31:50,700
-Did you forget your bullhorn, Sherry?
-Theo!

524
00:31:50,783 --> 00:31:53,244
If you have a theory,
make sure everyone hears it.

525
00:31:53,328 --> 00:31:55,038
Everyone knows what you're doing.

526
00:31:55,121 --> 00:31:57,457
You're trying to cash in
on someone else's tragedy,

527
00:31:57,540 --> 00:32:00,001
-so you can sell your vegan panties--
-Hey! Theo!

528
00:32:00,084 --> 00:32:01,878
And get all these likes on Instagram.

529
00:32:01,961 --> 00:32:03,546
Count to ten, okay? Relax.

530
00:32:04,297 --> 00:32:05,673
[thunder rumbling]

531
00:32:06,341 --> 00:32:07,884
Hey, Sherry, are you okay?

532
00:32:10,178 --> 00:32:12,764
He's having a very hard day.
He doesn't mean it.

533
00:32:12,847 --> 00:32:13,848
Right, Theo?

534
00:32:16,351 --> 00:32:17,602
You've done so much.

535
00:32:18,561 --> 00:32:20,521
How about we just get back to it?

536
00:32:21,397 --> 00:32:23,107
-Thank you.
-Of course.

537
00:32:24,108 --> 00:32:24,984
Let's go.

538
00:32:30,156 --> 00:32:32,200
-So that happened.
-"A hard day"?

539
00:32:33,910 --> 00:32:35,328
Fucking seriously?

540
00:32:47,465 --> 00:32:49,008
[thunder crashing]

541
00:32:49,092 --> 00:32:50,385
[door opens]

542
00:33:02,480 --> 00:33:03,606
[Fiona] Does it hurt, Joe?

543
00:33:06,693 --> 00:33:08,778
No idea why they did this to you?

544
00:33:08,861 --> 00:33:10,154
It doesn't matter.

545
00:33:10,238 --> 00:33:12,907
Counselors say I'm a lost cause.
I heard them.

546
00:33:12,991 --> 00:33:14,325
Hey, no, no.

547
00:33:15,034 --> 00:33:16,703
No kid is a lost cause.

548
00:33:17,870 --> 00:33:19,080
Especially not you.

549
00:33:24,752 --> 00:33:28,423
You know, if I were to adopt,
I would want an older kid.

550
00:33:28,506 --> 00:33:32,760
You know why?
Because... you know who they are.

551
00:33:33,970 --> 00:33:36,055
The whole messy truth.

552
00:33:37,265 --> 00:33:39,767
And that's beautiful and worthwhile.

553
00:33:40,435 --> 00:33:42,895
And exactly what I would want in my life.

554
00:33:44,772 --> 00:33:46,899
No matter what happened in the past,

555
00:33:48,526 --> 00:33:51,988
someone out there will want you too.
You're a good kid.

556
00:34:06,044 --> 00:34:06,878
[car alarm chirps]

557
00:34:11,924 --> 00:34:12,842
Excuse me, sir.

558
00:34:13,968 --> 00:34:14,969
You calling Uber?

559
00:34:17,805 --> 00:34:18,931
It's gonna rain. Get in.

560
00:34:23,770 --> 00:34:25,063
[cell phone buzzes]

561
00:34:28,733 --> 00:34:30,651
Is that your best friend Sherry?

562
00:34:36,866 --> 00:34:39,327
You know, it is really hard to stay mad

563
00:34:39,410 --> 00:34:42,371
at the one person
that I can actually stand talking to.

564
00:34:42,455 --> 00:34:44,791
Hmm. Stepdad still a brick wall?

565
00:34:47,376 --> 00:34:48,795
He's got a lot going on.

566
00:34:56,177 --> 00:34:57,595
But he's not a murderer.

567
00:35:01,974 --> 00:35:03,976
Hey, how did you deal with it?

568
00:35:04,060 --> 00:35:05,061
Like...

569
00:35:05,645 --> 00:35:08,231
all the attention and the rubbernecking?

570
00:35:08,314 --> 00:35:10,566
-You mean, about my brother?
-Yeah.

571
00:35:11,609 --> 00:35:14,862
-I read the Vanity Fair article, so...
-Mm-hm.

572
00:35:14,946 --> 00:35:18,866
He insisted that I cut his hair because
I was the only one that did it right.

573
00:35:19,450 --> 00:35:22,245
And he loved the Ninja Turtle movie.

574
00:35:23,246 --> 00:35:25,915
Uh, he always wanted to fast-forward
where the red one got hurt

575
00:35:25,998 --> 00:35:27,667
because it made him too sad.

576
00:35:29,001 --> 00:35:31,212
The shit that doesn't sell magazines.

577
00:35:33,005 --> 00:35:35,925
The part where he was
a whole fucking human being.

578
00:35:37,176 --> 00:35:38,845
The big,

579
00:35:39,762 --> 00:35:41,931
beautiful, sensitive fucking heart.

580
00:35:42,515 --> 00:35:44,725
He was the only person
who ever really knew me.

581
00:35:47,145 --> 00:35:47,979
You know...

582
00:35:49,689 --> 00:35:50,606
publicity...

583
00:35:51,899 --> 00:35:53,985
it has a way of flattening.

584
00:35:54,068 --> 00:35:56,988
Flattening you
and the people you love into types.

585
00:35:57,071 --> 00:36:01,159
And it's really hard because nobody
will ever let you forget what happened.

586
00:36:02,285 --> 00:36:03,161
Yeah.

587
00:36:18,843 --> 00:36:20,595
Rain snuck up on us.

588
00:36:20,678 --> 00:36:22,930
If it clears up soon,
we'll send people back out.

589
00:36:23,014 --> 00:36:26,350
You can be honest.
Today accomplished absolutely nothing.

590
00:36:26,434 --> 00:36:28,519
Besides something exciting
for the social media feeds

591
00:36:28,603 --> 00:36:30,771
of people that barely knew my wife.

592
00:36:31,397 --> 00:36:33,608
The search was always a long shot,

593
00:36:33,691 --> 00:36:36,485
and you had no belief whatsoever
we'd find anything. None.

594
00:36:36,569 --> 00:36:39,739
I've seen everything
up to this point, okay?

595
00:36:39,822 --> 00:36:42,116
And, yes, usually, you're right.

596
00:36:42,909 --> 00:36:45,077
Which isn't necessarily a bad thing.

597
00:36:45,620 --> 00:36:48,581
I mean, if we did find something...

598
00:36:48,664 --> 00:36:52,752
It would probably be something
that indicated she's not alive anymore.

599
00:36:57,006 --> 00:36:58,341
I know this is hard.

600
00:36:59,425 --> 00:37:02,261
And I'd just say to you,
let us keep working.

601
00:37:02,720 --> 00:37:05,139
-[dogs barking]
-[whistles blowing]

602
00:37:10,186 --> 00:37:11,854
[dramatic music playing]

603
00:37:20,529 --> 00:37:21,781
[Joe] Dearest Megy,

604
00:37:22,657 --> 00:37:25,493
my heart aches as I write this.

605
00:37:25,576 --> 00:37:27,787
[Gil] You stood by me in spite of my flaws

606
00:37:27,870 --> 00:37:30,539
and Lord knows you don't deserve
what I've done to you.

607
00:37:30,623 --> 00:37:33,084
I strayed. No excuse.

608
00:37:33,167 --> 00:37:37,046
Idiot me thought Natalie could
provide something I was missing.

609
00:37:37,129 --> 00:37:40,716
When it became clear
she'd never belong exclusively to me,

610
00:37:40,800 --> 00:37:42,051
I lost control.

611
00:37:42,593 --> 00:37:44,804
I do not know what came over me.

612
00:37:44,887 --> 00:37:49,642
Next thing I knew, I was standing there,
with an ax, her body on the ground.

613
00:37:49,725 --> 00:37:51,852
And when I put her in the ocean,

614
00:37:52,561 --> 00:37:55,106
I felt like I was possessed
by someone else.

615
00:37:55,815 --> 00:37:59,443
But I am guilty all the same,
and I can't live with what I've done.

616
00:38:00,194 --> 00:38:03,656
I'm sorry I hurt you.
And I'm sorry you found me like this.

617
00:38:03,739 --> 00:38:06,867
I failed all of you. But especially Alan.

618
00:38:07,576 --> 00:38:10,955
Didn't want to see in him
what I saw in myself.

619
00:38:11,038 --> 00:38:13,499
Maybe you can mold him into a better man.

620
00:38:14,292 --> 00:38:16,377
Tell him and the girls I love them.

621
00:38:18,629 --> 00:38:23,050
And know that I love you, Megy.

622
00:38:24,218 --> 00:38:25,928
More than you'll ever know.

623
00:38:27,930 --> 00:38:28,848
[Joe] Forgive me,

624
00:38:31,183 --> 00:38:32,518
Your Gily.

625
00:38:34,020 --> 00:38:38,899
Yeah, well, someone wrote a think piece
about my parents' divorce.

626
00:38:39,358 --> 00:38:40,276
Yeah.

627
00:38:40,359 --> 00:38:43,070
It was about the first wives
of tech superstars

628
00:38:43,154 --> 00:38:45,948
and how Silicon Valley discards women.

629
00:38:48,409 --> 00:38:51,412
Thought that was the worst thing
that ever happened to me.

630
00:38:51,495 --> 00:38:55,041
Yeah, look at you now.
Got a family tragedy all your own.

631
00:38:58,002 --> 00:39:00,421
I'm not trying to sound flip. It's just--

632
00:39:02,298 --> 00:39:04,592
-Welcome to the club.
-Mm. Do I get a gift bag?

633
00:39:05,760 --> 00:39:10,848
Or does terrible family tragedy
make people more fuckable?

634
00:39:11,390 --> 00:39:14,685
'Cause... Could really use
a silver lining.

635
00:39:14,769 --> 00:39:16,020
Um...

636
00:39:16,896 --> 00:39:19,357
In my experience, yes, but...

637
00:39:20,191 --> 00:39:22,818
you end up resenting
the people who think that fucking you

638
00:39:22,902 --> 00:39:25,738
was somehow gonna make them
more interesting.

639
00:39:25,821 --> 00:39:28,449
Like it's gonna rub off on them
or something.

640
00:39:29,325 --> 00:39:31,619
Don't let people like that define you.

641
00:39:39,001 --> 00:39:40,336
Find the people that get you.

642
00:39:41,212 --> 00:39:42,421
Lean on them.

643
00:39:42,505 --> 00:39:45,633
Forty-- My brother, he never really...

644
00:39:46,926 --> 00:39:47,760
got that.

645
00:39:54,225 --> 00:39:56,602
So how do you know who those people are?

646
00:39:57,395 --> 00:39:58,396
You just do.

647
00:40:05,486 --> 00:40:06,529
Um...

648
00:40:10,157 --> 00:40:11,367
-Don't do that.
-Yep.

649
00:40:13,536 --> 00:40:15,413
[cell phone buzzing]

650
00:40:15,496 --> 00:40:18,499
Oh, shit. I got a text from my dad.

651
00:40:18,582 --> 00:40:20,459
Whoa. They think they found something.

652
00:40:21,377 --> 00:40:24,630
They think they might have just found
a murder weapon.

653
00:40:36,434 --> 00:40:37,601
Morning, everybody.

654
00:40:38,394 --> 00:40:41,522
I'm Detective Falco
with the Madre Linda Police Department.

655
00:40:41,605 --> 00:40:44,608
There's been a development
in the Natalie Engler investigation.

656
00:40:44,692 --> 00:40:47,862
New evidence points to a suspect
in her disappearance

657
00:40:47,945 --> 00:40:50,990
-and potentially her murder.
-[Joe] We are hardly criminal masterminds.

658
00:40:51,073 --> 00:40:52,032
Gily?

659
00:40:53,701 --> 00:40:55,286
I got your text, honey.

660
00:40:55,369 --> 00:40:58,456
I don't know why you insisted
on the kids staying with my mother.

661
00:40:59,623 --> 00:41:02,835
[Joe] But sometimes
all it takes is a good story.

662
00:41:03,836 --> 00:41:06,547
Make it solid, sexy, relatable.

663
00:41:10,050 --> 00:41:12,553
Give them just enough evidence.

664
00:41:12,636 --> 00:41:14,930
[reporter] It has come to our attention
that Mrs. Engler

665
00:41:15,014 --> 00:41:16,849
was involved
in an extramarital relationship

666
00:41:16,932 --> 00:41:19,185
with Madre Linda resident Gil Brigham,

667
00:41:19,268 --> 00:41:21,604
a professor at Stanford University.

668
00:41:22,188 --> 00:41:26,025
In a letter, Mr. Brigham confessed
he murdered Mrs. Engler and disposed...

669
00:41:26,108 --> 00:41:31,113
[Joe] And the town of Madre Linda settles
into begrudging acceptance

670
00:41:31,197 --> 00:41:34,533
that the sordid tale
of suburban ennui, sex and murder

671
00:41:34,617 --> 00:41:36,160
has come to an end

672
00:41:36,243 --> 00:41:40,164
'cause, well, what bored suburbanite
isn't gonna buy that?

673
00:41:50,257 --> 00:41:51,926
We did it, Love.

674
00:41:52,009 --> 00:41:54,970
Let's be honest,
rebuilding the cage was crazy.

675
00:41:55,054 --> 00:41:58,098
Could've really backfired.
And yet it worked.

676
00:41:58,641 --> 00:42:00,100
We slowed down.

677
00:42:01,060 --> 00:42:02,353
Reflected.

678
00:42:02,436 --> 00:42:03,687
Responded.

679
00:42:04,772 --> 00:42:07,775
Proved we're a team. For Henry.

680
00:42:08,734 --> 00:42:10,069
[engine starting]

681
00:42:20,454 --> 00:42:22,665
You look terrible, Herr Gynt.

682
00:42:31,924 --> 00:42:32,925
Oh.

683
00:42:33,008 --> 00:42:35,928
-Sorry, a lot of long nights.
-Yeah, it's fine.

684
00:42:36,637 --> 00:42:40,307
Dante was an absolute liability
when their younger was small.

685
00:42:40,391 --> 00:42:42,643
Just forgot the Dewey Decimal System,

686
00:42:42,726 --> 00:42:47,147
despite it literally being printed
on every aisle, in Braille.

687
00:42:47,231 --> 00:42:48,732
[Joe] She's being nice to me.

688
00:42:48,816 --> 00:42:51,569
Weird to think disclosing
one's shit childhood could do that.

689
00:42:51,652 --> 00:42:54,572
Hers must not have been
exactly roses either.

690
00:42:54,655 --> 00:42:56,156
You have a kid, right?

691
00:42:57,575 --> 00:42:59,994
-Mm-hm.
-How do you balance it?

692
00:43:00,077 --> 00:43:03,372
She's with her dad these days.

693
00:43:03,455 --> 00:43:05,666
[Joe] And she throws that away. Curious.

694
00:43:05,749 --> 00:43:08,168
Guess I don't need to ask if you've heard

695
00:43:08,252 --> 00:43:12,131
about the whole awful Gil Brigham thing.

696
00:43:12,214 --> 00:43:14,550
Yeah. Yeah, it's terrible.

697
00:43:14,633 --> 00:43:15,467
Truly.

698
00:43:16,885 --> 00:43:18,721
Does mean we need a new reader.

699
00:43:18,804 --> 00:43:20,806
-You still interested?
-Sure.

700
00:43:21,432 --> 00:43:22,933
-Of course.
-Great.

701
00:43:23,017 --> 00:43:26,145
Oh, and I have a new rec for you.

702
00:43:27,855 --> 00:43:28,939
David Copperfield.

703
00:43:29,023 --> 00:43:31,734
You know, hardscrabble orphan
down on his luck.

704
00:43:31,817 --> 00:43:33,444
Figured you could relate.

705
00:43:33,527 --> 00:43:35,237
[Joe] She's teasing me, isn't she?

706
00:43:35,321 --> 00:43:38,616
-Ha.
-Anyway, if you wanted to apply

707
00:43:38,699 --> 00:43:42,077
your wizard-level book repair skills,
have at it.

708
00:43:42,786 --> 00:43:47,041
[Joe] It's almost like
you're flirting with me?

709
00:43:47,124 --> 00:43:50,002
No. No, you wouldn't.
Well, not consciously.

710
00:43:51,086 --> 00:43:54,423
This necklace thing, nervous habit?

711
00:43:54,506 --> 00:43:59,303
Why would you be nervous unless...?
It couldn't be about me. Could it?

712
00:43:59,386 --> 00:44:00,721
You okay there, Joe?

713
00:44:00,804 --> 00:44:03,599
[Joe] Oh, shit. What was I just doing?

714
00:44:03,682 --> 00:44:05,893
-I'm totally fine.
-Great.

715
00:44:06,810 --> 00:44:09,480
[Joe] I cannot be thinking
about you like this. No.

716
00:44:13,525 --> 00:44:16,111
No, no, no. This is bad.

717
00:44:21,116 --> 00:44:22,493
[theme music playing]
